{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85a675af-85b9-430c-be48-2d8b1a077c6f","content":"In .NET MAUI, the `Application`-level `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume` overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to them:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\nFor **platform-specific** hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b62ebaa7-6f42-40e9-95d7-9e16f5999f17","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleEventHandler` approach. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` â†’ `Window.Created` event or override `CreateWindow`\n- `OnSleep` â†’ `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`\n\n\n- `OnResume` â†’ `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`\n\nThe key difference is that .NET MAUI manages the application lifecycle through the `Window` class instead of the `Application` class. You can override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class and subscribe to window events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying` to handle the lifecycle transitions.\n\nFor more granular control, there's also `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` that lets you hook into platform-specific lifecycle events.","outputTokens":739},"id":"f82665d9-e768-4eb1-8a89-3695d89c085b","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:46:44.434Z","parentId":"d6a60d6f-c435-4114-9a13-e20c7b9320df"}
